The unexpected behaviour described in the question is determined by a custom drawing of the OwnerDrawn ComboBox (a Custom Control derived from ComboBox).  

When the DataSource of a ListControl is a complex object - as in this case, a [DataTable.DefaultView][1] (a [DataView][2]) - each Item in the list is a complex object itself, a [`DataRowView`][3] here.  

For this reason, when drawing the Items of an OwnerDrawn ListControl (overriding the `OnDrawItem` method), the Item&#39;s text, as displayed in the Control&#39;s visible area, should be fetched using the ListControl&#39;s [GetItemText()][4] method.  

This method fetches an Item&#39;s text (using the internal Datamanager if a DataSource has beed defined, or the TypeDescriptor if not), no matter what the Item&#39;s Type is:   

&gt; If the DisplayMember property is not specified, the value returned by
&gt; GetItemText(Object) is the value of the item&#39;s ToString method.
&gt; Otherwise, the method returns the string value of the member specified
&gt; in the DisplayMember property for the object specified in the item
&gt; parameter.

[.Net Source code of ListControl.GetItemText()][5]  

A classic mistake when drawing an Item&#39;s text it to convert to string the Item&#39;s object:  
This can work if the Item&#39;s text is a simple string, not if it&#39;s a complex object. In this case **`[ComplexObject].ToString()`** returns the object&#39;s data type (`System.Data.DataRowView`, in this case).  

    protected override void OnDrawItem(DrawItemEventArgs e)
    {
        // (...)
        e.DrawBackground();
        using (var brush = new SolidBrush(this.ForeColor)) {
            e.Graphics.DrawString(this.Items[e.Index].ToString()), this.Font, brush, e.Bounds);
        }
        // (...)
    }

&lt;sup&gt;Simplified sample code, do not use :)&lt;/sup&gt;


Using **`GetItemText()`**, the property value of `DisplayMember` is returned as a string. Since `comboBox1.DisplayMember = &quot;Display&quot;;`, it will return the content of the DataTable&#39;s `Display` Column.  

    protected override void OnDrawItem(DrawItemEventArgs e)
    {
        // (...)
        e.DrawBackground();
        using (var brush = new SolidBrush(this.ForeColor)) {
            e.Graphics.DrawString(this.GetItemText(this.Items[e.Index]), this.Font, brush, e.Bounds);
        }
        // (...)
    }


  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.data.datatable.defaultview
  [2]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.data.dataview
  [3]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.data.datarowview
  [4]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.windows.forms.listcontrol.getitemtext
  [5]: https://referencesource.microsoft.com/#System.Windows.Forms/winforms/Managed/System/WinForms/ListControl.cs,555

